{# goal: Classify mapped findings into OSC&R categories + OWASP Supply Chain dual taxonomy. Produce pattern signatures for detecting similar attack patterns. Propose optional, backward-compatible taxonomy_mapping field additions to existing surface: supply-chain regression entries. Emit cns.taxonomy.report span (P9) — namespace registered in CANONICAL_NAMESPACES (event.rs). Produce verdict (Pass / Conditional / Fail). Replicant_host mandatory (P12). No invented OSC&R categories. Registry authoritative (P5.1). #}
{# Classifies mapped findings into OSC&R + OWASP SC dual taxonomy #}
{# Produces pattern signatures for similar attack pattern detection #}
{# Proposes backward-compatible taxonomy_mapping field for regression YAML #}
{# Emits cns.taxonomy.report CNS span (P9) — namespace registered #}

INPUT: mappings = {{ mappings }} (structured array from map-taxonomy phase)
INPUT: unmapped_findings = {{ unmapped_findings | default([]) }} (from map-taxonomy)
INPUT: mapping_counts = {{ mapping_counts | default({}) }} (from map-taxonomy)
INPUT: existing_regressions = {{ existing_regressions | default([]) }} (from select-evidence — regressions_needing_mapping)
INPUT: replicant_host = {{ replicant_host | default("REQUIRED") }} (P12 — no anonymous classification)

CLASSIFICATION ACTIONS (concrete — evidence-backed only, P8):
1. Group `mappings` by `osc_r_category`. For each OSC&R category,
   produce a category summary:
   - `osc_r_category` (e.g., `dependency_confusion`)
   - `findings_count`
   - `findings` (list of `finding_reference`s in this category)
   - `cwe_references` (set of CWE categories observed in this group)
   - `owasp_sc_categories` (set of OWASP SC categories observed)
   - `defense_gap_count` (how many findings in this category lack a
     corresponding defense layer)
   - `variety_gap_count` (how many findings have alternative vectors
     uncovered)
   - `regulator_strength_summary` ({enforcing, advisory, missing} counts)
   - `pattern_signature` (concrete detection pattern — see step 3)
2. Group `mappings` by `owasp_sc_category`. For each OWASP SC category,
   produce a parallel summary (same fields, keyed by OWASP SC).
3. Produce `pattern_signature` per OSC&R category — a concrete detection
   pattern (regex or structural predicate) for finding similar attack
   patterns in future audits. Pattern signatures must reference
   concrete manifest/CI content (not vague descriptions):
   - `dependency_confusion`: regex matching package names not in
     private registry but available publicly (e.g., `cargo` manifest
     entry with name matching public crates.io package not in
     workspace's private registry allowlist).
   - `typosquatting`: Levenshtein distance ≤2 between dependency name
     and canonical name (concrete algorithm, not vague description).
   - `malicious_commit_injection`: `git = "..."` dependency without
     `rev = "<full-sha>"` pinning (regex against Cargo.toml).
   - `build_pipeline_compromise`: GitHub Actions `uses:` field without
     `@<full-sha>` pinning (regex against `.github/workflows/*.yml`).
   - `unmaintained_component`: dependency with no `deny.toml`
     advisory-bypass entry and version spec referencing a stale
     registry entry (concrete: `Cargo.toml` version + `Cargo.lock`
     version mismatch, or `deny.toml` `bypass` entry).
   - `unverified_registry`: `git = ...` or `path = ...` dependency
     without `registry = "..."` reference (regex against Cargo.toml).
   Each pattern_signature must be a concrete grep-able pattern —
   not a description. Cite the manifest/CI file the pattern targets.
4. For each regression in `existing_regressions` (regressions with
   `surface: supply-chain` and `cwe` field but no `taxonomy_mapping`
   field), propose a backward-compatible `taxonomy_mapping` field
   addition. Format (per security/regressions/README.md — optional
   field, existing regressions without it remain valid):
   ```yaml
   taxonomy_mapping:
     osc_r: "<osc_r_category_id>"   # e.g., "dependency_confusion"
     owasp_sc: "<SCxx>"              # e.g., "SC04"
   ```
   Each proposal must include:
   - `regression_id` (e.g., `RR-0123`)
   - `cwe_reference` (from the regression's existing `cwe` field)
   - `proposed_taxonomy_mapping` (the YAML snippet above)
   - `evidence_reference` (which finding from `mappings` justified
     this proposal — traceable to upstream evidence)
   - `mapping_confidence` (from the mapping)
   - `status: pending` (human-curated ratchet — P11 visibility;
     human must flip to `enforced` after review)
5. Identify top 3 taxonomy coverage gaps:
   - OSC&R categories with zero mappings (attack patterns we have
     no findings for — may indicate audit blind spot, not absence).
   - OWASP SC categories with zero mappings.
   - Findings with `defense_gap: true` and `regulator_strength:
     missing` (highest-priority remediation targets).
6. Produce verdict:
   - Pass: zero unmapped findings, all OSC&R categories with evidence
     have ≥1 mapping, all proposed taxonomy_mapping fields have
     `mapping_confidence: high`.
   - Conditional: 1-5 unmapped findings, OR some mappings with
     `mapping_confidence: medium`, OR some `defense_gap: true`.
   - Fail: >5 unmapped findings, OR any critical/high finding
     unmapped, OR any OSC&R category with evidence but zero
     defense-layer coverage (`regulator_strength: missing` for all
     findings in that category).

CNS SPAN EMISSION (P9):
- `cns.taxonomy.report` is registered in `CANONICAL_NAMESPACES`
  (`crates/hkask-types/src/event.rs`). Emit span unconditionally:
  (`target: "cns.taxonomy.report"`, message: `"CNS"`,
  operation: `"taxonomize"`, mappings_count, unmapped_count,
  osc_r_categories_covered, owasp_sc_categories_covered,
  proposed_taxonomy_mappings_count, verdict, replicant_host,
  latency_ms).

CONSTRAINTS (P5 minimalism, P8 evidence integrity, P12 host):
- No invented OSC&R categories — only classify into categories
  present in `mappings` (which came from map-taxonomy's verified
  `osc_r_categories` list).
- No synthetic findings — only classify `mappings` from map-taxonomy.
- Every pattern_signature must be a concrete grep-able pattern
  (regex or structural predicate) — not a vague description.
- Every proposed `taxonomy_mapping` field must be backward-
  compatible (optional field — existing regressions without it
  remain valid YAML).
- Every proposed `taxonomy_mapping` must include `evidence_reference`
  traceable to a mapping in `mappings` — no fabricated proposals.
- `status: pending` only — never `enforced` (human-curated ratchet,
  P11 visibility).
- `visibility: public` — no hidden classification controls (P3, P4).
- Registry (this manifest.yaml + templates) is authoritative over
  SKILL.md (P5.1).
- Every output includes `replicant_host` identity (P12).
- Do NOT propose `taxonomy_mapping` for regressions that already
  have one (skip — P5 minimalism, no duplicate work).
- Do NOT propose `taxonomy_mapping` for regressions without a `cwe`
  field (cannot map without CWE reference — record as
  `unmappable_regression` with reason).

OUTPUT FORMAT:
JSON object with fields:
`osc_r_classification` (grouped by OSC&R category — see step 1),
`owasp_sc_classification` (grouped by OWASP SC category — see step 2),
`pattern_signatures` (per OSC&R category — concrete grep-able patterns),
`proposed_taxonomy_mappings` (array of {regression_id, cwe_reference,
proposed_taxonomy_mapping, evidence_reference, mapping_confidence,
status: "pending"}), `taxonomy_coverage_gaps` (top 3 — see step 5),
`unmappable_regressions` (regressions without cwe field — with reason),
`verdict` (`Pass` | `Conditional` | `Fail`),
`verdict_rationale` (concrete — references unmapped count, defense gaps,
mapping confidence), `replicant_host`, `cns_span_emitted: true`.

5W1H GATE CHECK (P5): Who = replicant host (P12); What = OSC&R +
OWASP SC classification + pattern signatures + taxonomy_mapping
proposals; Where = mappings array (from map-taxonomy) +
existing_regressions; When = taxonomize phase (after map-taxonomy);
Why = P8 semantic grounding (structured attack-pattern context) /
P9 observable regulation / P11 visibility (regression proposals
public, status: pending); How = group by category → produce pattern
signatures → propose taxonomy_mapping field → identify gaps →
produce verdict → emit CNS span.
All 6 present — passes gate.

RELATIONSHIP (explicit): Consumes mappings from map-taxonomy.
Produces classification + pattern signatures + taxonomy_mapping
proposals consumed by humans (regression review) and by
convergence-check (coverage metric). Does NOT overlap with
supply-chain-sentinel (which proposes surface: supply-chain
regressions with CWE mappings — this skill adds the
taxonomy_mapping FIELD to those regressions, backward-compatible).
Does NOT overlap with kali-audit (which classifies into OWASP LLM
/ ATLAS — this skill classifies into OSC&R + OWASP SC). Does NOT
overlap with bug-hunt's taxonomize phase (which classifies into
Beizer's bug taxonomy — this skill classifies into OSC&R attack
taxonomy). P5 minimalism: each phase answers one 5W1H dimension.
taxonomize answers WHY + WHAT (classification rationale).

MINIMAL: One template (`KnowAct`); no extra scanning; uses mappings
from map-taxonomy only; no synthetic classifications.

EVIDENCE-BACKED ONLY (P8): Every classification entry traces to a
mapping in `mappings`. Every proposed taxonomy_mapping traces to a
mapping via `evidence_reference`. Pattern signatures reference
concrete manifest/CI file content. No fabricated classifications.

EVOLUTIONARY (P7): New pattern signatures can be added as new
attack patterns are observed in mappings — but only from real
evidence, not speculation.

OCAP BOUNDARY (P4): Classifies mappings and proposes regression
field additions only; no external taxonomy database download; no
ambient scanning; no regression enforcement (human-curated ratchet).

CNS REGULATION (P9): `cns.taxonomy.report` emitted unconditionally
— namespace registered in `CANONICAL_NAMESPACES` (event.rs).

REPLICANT HOST (P12): `replicant_host` mandatory in all outputs.

VISIBILITY (P11): Classification output public; proposed
taxonomy_mappings `status: pending` — human-curated ratchet, not
hidden control.

SAFETY FLOOR (P3.1): Structured attack-pattern classification
protects Generative Space — unmapped findings leave incident
response ambiguous.

